EDA is open-ended, and it is up to you to decide how to look at different ways to slice and dice your data. A good starting point is to look at the requirements for the FDA documentation in the final part of this project to guide (some) of the analyses you do.

This EDA should also help to inform you of how pneumonia looks in the wild. E.g. what other types of diseases it's commonly found with, how often it is found, what ages it affects, etc.

Note that this NIH dataset was not specifically acquired for pneumonia. So, while this is a representation of 'pneumonia in the wild,' the prevalence of pneumonia may be different if you were to take only chest x-rays that were acquired in an ER setting with suspicion of pneumonia.

Perform the following EDA:

  • The patient demographic data such as gender, age, patient position,etc. (as it is available)
  • The x-ray views taken (i.e. view position)
  • The number of cases including:
    • number of pneumonia cases,
    • number of non-pneumonia cases
  • The distribution of other diseases that are comorbid with pneumonia
  • Number of disease per patient
  • Pixel-level assessments of the imaging data for healthy & disease states of interest (e.g. histograms of intensity values) and compare distributions across diseases.

Note: use full NIH data to perform the first a few EDA items and use sample_labels.csv for the pixel-level assassements.

Also, describe your findings and how will you set up the model training based on the findings.

Findings from EDA¶

  • There is a slight difference in the number of Female Vs Male present in the data, 14560 male are more than female in data.Similar difference is noted in patients with Pneumonia diagnosed
  • Most of the patients in NIH data lies in age group 50-60
  • Penumonia is diagnosed for almost all age groups, majority of case lies in 30-70 age group and the most cases are reported for 55-65 age group
  • There are 2 distinct view position of X-ray ('PA', 'AP'), in overall dataset, x-rays of 'PA' view position (almost 70000) is more than 'AP' position (45000) but Pneomonia is present mostly in 'AP' x-ray position
  • In overall dataset only 1.3 % cases are of Pneumonia, rest of 98.7 % are of non pneomonia, also in terms of gender specific diagnosis as well pneumonia is found very less in both Male and female in the overall dataset
  • Most of the Pneomonia cases appears alone, the next major comorbidity is Infiltration, Edema+Infiltration, Atelectasis, Edema, Effusion
  • No. of disease per patient is mostly 1 and sometime it is either 2, 3, and 4 and rarely reaches to 9

In [32]:
fig,axes = plt.subplots(3,3, figsize=(15,15))
fig.tight_layout()

normal_data = sample_df[sample_df['Finding Labels'] == 'No Finding'].sample(3)
img_paths = [glob(f"/data/images*/*/{i}")[0] for i in normal_data['Image Index'].values]
for idx, each in enumerate(img_paths[:3]):
    ds = plt.imread(each)
#     print(ds)
    ds_flat = np.array(ds).ravel()
    mean = ds_flat.mean()
    std = np.std(ds_flat)
    normal = (ds_flat - mean) / std
    axes[0, idx].set_title(normal_data[normal_data['Image Index']== each.split('/')[-1]]['Finding Labels'].values[0])
    axes[0, idx].axis('Off')
    axes[0, idx].imshow(ds, cmap='gray')
    axes[1, idx].hist(np.array(ds).ravel(), bins = 256,color='green')
    axes[2, idx].hist(normal, bins = 256,color='blue')

Finding from intensity distribution¶

By looking at the intensity distribution of No finding, Pneomonia and Infiltration, I don't see any similarity in similar cases; which makes it an unreliable way to study these x-rays
